{
  "doc_id": "45454",
  "text": "The Route kernel [CITATION_1] computes the matching between two trees in terms of number of common routes, that is the shortest path linking two nodes in a tree represented by the sequence of edge indices. A similar approach is taken in [CITATION_2] where the kernel function is defined in terms of subpath sets that are routes capturing vertical structures in rooted unordered trees. The subpath kernel has also an efficient version [CITATION_3] that is O(N 2 T ) in worst case but can run in linear time on average. Other proposed tree kernels are reviewed in [CITATION_4] and [CITATION_5] .",
